{"cursor":"3292","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'' by Pierre Denys de Montfort]] 'Pierre Denys de Montfort', also sometimes\nspelled \"Pierre DÃ©nys de Montfort\", (1766â1820) was a French naturalist, in\nparticular a malacologist, remembered today for his pioneering inquiries into\nthe existence of the giant squid [[Architeuthis]], which was thought to be an\nold wives' tale, and for which he was long dismissed. He was inspired by a\ndescription from 1783 of an eight-metre long tentacle found in the mouth of a\nsperm whale.\n\nMontfort was author of Conchyliologie systÃ©matique, et classification mÃ©thodique\nde coquilles (2 vols., Paris 1808â1810) and of Histoire Naturelle GÃ©nÃ©rale et\nParticuliÃ¨re des Mollusques (2 vols., Paris 1801â1802) published as an addendum\nto the comte de Buffon's Histoire naturelle gÃ©nÃ©rale et particuliÃ¨re.\n\nHe appears also to have been the author of Petit vocabulaire Ã  l'usage des\nFranÃ§ais et des AlliÃ©s, renfermant les noms d'une partie des choses les plus\nessentielles Ã  la vie en plusieurs langues: franÃ§ais, Latin, hÃ©breu, hollandais,\nallemand, anglais, espagnol, italien, etc par M. Denys de Montfort, [http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/epc/langueXIX/rep_bib/1815-\n19.htm] accessed 24 April 2011. which appeared in 1815, as Paris filled\nwith the polyglot armies of the Allies, after the fall of Napoleon in 1814.\n\nMontfort later dared more sensational claims. He proposed that ten British\nwarships that had mysteriously disappeared one night in 1782 must have been\nattacked and sunk by giant octopuses. Unfortunately for Montfort, the British\nknew what had happened to the ships, resulting in a disgraceful revelation for\nMontfort. His career never recovered and he died starving and poor in Paris\naround 1820. SjÃ¶gren, Bengt (1980). BerÃ¶mda vidunder. Settern. ISBN 91-7586-023-\n6 Many of his sources for the \"kraken octopus\" probably described the very\nreal giant squid, [[Architeuthis]], proven to